\title{Spectral theory on $\textit{L}^2$: kernel operators and Hamiltonian }
\author{Arthur L. Limoge\textsuperscript}
\institute{\textsuperscript \, Imperial College London}
\titlegraphic{\includegraphics[width=0.06\textwidth]{logo.png}}

\begin{document}
\maketitle
\centering

\begin{columns}
    \column{0.32}
    \block{$\textit{L}^2\,$ as a Hilbert Space}{
         
        \hspace*{10mm} At the start of the 20th century, progress in analysis, especially spectral theory, 
         
         \begin{minipage}{0.75\linewidth}
                  \vspace{-1.5em}
         led to define Hilbert spaces, and hence generalize notions previously established by figures including Fourier or Parseval. In particular, operator theory developed a lot under the influence of mathematicians such as Frigyes Riesz, who defined $L^p$ spaces for the first time. 
         
         \smallskip
         
         Formally, for $p \in \mathbb{N}^{*},$ and $(X,\mathcal{F}, \mu)$ a measure space:
         
         \end{minipage}
         \hfill
         \begin{minipage}{0.2\linewidth}
         \begin{tikzfigure}[Frigyes  Riesz]
         \includegraphics[scale=0.5]{beaugosse.jpg}
         \end{tikzfigure}
         \end{minipage}
       
         
         
         \begin{align*}
            L^p(X) := \{f : \displaystyle\int_X |f|^p \mathrm{d}\mu < +\infty \}
        \end{align*}
        
        \medskip
        
        In the following, we will simply consider $X$ to be a subset of $\mathbb{R}$, $\mu$ to be the Lebesgue measure, and we will focus on the case $p = 2$.
         
        \medskip
        
        For $X \subseteq \mathbb{R}, L^2(X)$ is a Hilbert Space. Its inner product is indeed well-defined due to the linearity of integration $\left(\text{where }\braket{f|g}\footnote{1} = \displaystyle\int_X g(x)f(x)\mathrm{d}x\right)$; and the space has been proven to be complete by the Riesz-Fischer theorem [\cite{1}]. We will here zoom in on integral operators of the form:
        
        \begin{align*}
         \, \mathcal{T}: \begin{array}{ccccc}  & \, & L^2(X) & \to & L^2(X) \\  & & f & \mapsto & \left(x\mapsto \displaystyle\int_X K(x,y)f(y) \mathrm{d}y\right) \\ \end{array} 
        \end{align*}
        
        \normalsize{where $K : \mathbb{R}^2 \to \mathbb{R}$} is called the kernel of the transform.
            \vspace{2em}
    }
    

    \block{Study of the spectrum}{
    

    \large
       \hspace*{10mm} The spectrum of an operator is a generalization [\cite{3}] of the set of eigenvalues to infinite dimension:
        
        \medskip
        
        For two vectors $\ket{\chi}, \ket{\varphi}$ in a Hilbert space $\mathcal{H}$, and $z \in \mathbb{K},$ consider the equation
        
        \begin{equation}
            (zI - T)\ket{\chi} = \ket{\varphi}
            \label{eq:1}
        \end{equation}
        
        \medskip
        
        If the image of $(zI - T)$ ($I$ being the identity) is $\mathcal{H}$, then $z$ is said to be a \textbf{regular value} of $T$, and the resolvent $(zI - T)^{-1}$ is well-defined. The spectrum is then defined to be the set of non-regular values of $T$.  In our case, $\mathcal{H} = L^2(X)$, $X$ being a subset of $\mathbb{R}$.
        
        \medskip
        
        In some simple cases, this eigenvalue problem can be brought down to a linear algebra one. For example, with the operator satisfying $Tf(x) = \int K(x,y)f(y)\mathrm{d}y :$
        
        \medskip
        
        \begin{minipage}{0.8\linewidth}
        \bigskip
        \bigskip
        
        
    \normalsize
         \begin{wrapfigure}{r}{0.01\linewidth}
\vspace{-2em} \resizebox{5.8cm}{1.3cm}{\xymatrix{
    V \ar[r]^{T} \ar[d]_u  & V \ar[d]^u  \\
    \mathbb{R}^n \ar[r]_A & \mathbb{R}^n \\
  } }  
\end{wrapfigure}
Assume $K(x,y) = \displaystyle\sum\limits_{k=1}^{n} \varphi_k(x)\psi_k(y)$ is the kernel of an operator $T$, where $\{\varphi_k\}$ and $\{\psi_k\}$ are sets of functions, and the $\ket{\varphi_k}$ are linearly independent (call $V$ their span). Solving the eigenvalue problem is equivalent to diagonalizing the associated matrix in the side diagram; where $u$ denotes the  natural isomorphism $V \to \mathbb{R}^n$. We can check it by taking $\ket{f} \in V$, and then following the diagram to get $Au(\ket{f}) = u(T\ket{f})$.


        
        \end{minipage}
        

    }

    \column{0.36}
    \block{Norm of operators}{
    
   \hspace*{10mm} The norm of an operator $T$ is defined as $||T||_2 := \sup\limits_{f \ne 0} \dfrac{\braket{Tf|f}}{||f||^2}$. Its knowledge is quite useful because it provides an upper bound for the eigenvalues of the transform, [\cite{4}]. However, some do not have eigenvalues. For instance, consider the operator $\mathcal{K}$ with kernel $K : (x,y) \mapsto \dfrac{1}{x+y}$, on $L^2(\mathbb{R}_+)$.

\bigskip

It has no (non-zero) eigenvalues, but it still has a non-empty spectrum: the function defined by $x \mapsto x^{-1/2}$ does not belong to $L^2(\mathbb{R}_+)$, but one can note that:

\medskip
        
        \begin{equation}
       \displaystyle\int_{0}^{+\infty} \dfrac{1}{x+y}y^{-1/2} \mathrm{d}y = \pi x^{-1/2} \text{ (proved by setting } t=\frac{\sqrt{y}}{\sqrt{x}})
       \end{equation}
       
       \vspace{1em}
       
       Therefore, the spectrum contains $\pi$, which we can prove is an upper bound for the norm. Indeed, take $\ket{f} \in L^2(\mathbb{R}_+)$ and consider:
       

       
       \begin{align*}
           \braket{Kf|f} & = \displaystyle\iint_{0}^{+\infty} \dfrac{f(y)f(x)}{x+y} \mathrm{d}y\,\mathrm{d}x =
           \displaystyle\iint_{0}^{+\infty} \dfrac{f(xt)f(x)}{1 + t} \mathrm{d}t \mathrm{d}x \left(\text{set } y = tx) \\
            & = \displaystyle\int_{0}^{+\infty} \dfrac{\braket{f(x)|f(xt)}}{1+t} \mathrm{d}t
            \hspace{0.5em} \leq \displaystyle\int_{0}^{+\infty} \dfrac{1}{1+t}\times \dfrac{||f||}{\sqrt{t}}||f|| \,\mathrm{d}t \left(\text{\normalsize{Cauchy-Schwarz}}\right) \\
            & =||f||^2 \displaystyle\int_{0}^{+\infty} \frac{t^{-1/2}}{1+t} \mathrm{d}t \hspace{1em} = \pi ||f||^2 \implies ||K||_2 \leq \pi. 
       \end{align*}
       
       \hline
       
       \bigskip
       
       \large
       
       \hspace*{10mm}As-a-matter-of-fact, this norm \textbf{\underline{is}} $\pi$: note that though the function $x \mapsto x^{-1/2}$ is not in $L^2$;
      
      \vspace{-1.5em}
       
       \[
\text{for $a > 1$, the function defined by  $f_a(x) =$}
\left \{
\begin{array}
    \, x^{-1/2} \text{ if } 0 < x < a \\
    0 \text{ else} 
    \end{array}
\right.
\text{ \textbf{is}\footnote{2}. And by taking bigger values}
\]

\vspace{-1em}

of $a$, we can expect $\dfrac{\braket{Kf_a|f_a}}{||f_a||^2}$ to get arbitrarily close to $\pi$:
        
  \begin{tikzfigure}[Plot of the curve $y = x^{-1/2}\times Kf_a(x)$. The yellow area represents $\braket{Kf_a|f_a}$.]
\begin{tikzpicture}[loveofmylife.jpg, scale = 2.2]
\begin{axis}[domain=0:100,
    yticklabel style = {font=\scriptsize,xshift=0.5ex},
    xticklabel style = {font=\scriptsize,xshift=0.5ex},
    xscale=1,yscale=1,
    xmin=0, xmax=100,
    ymin=0, ymax= 0.1,
    samples=501,
    axis lines=center,
    extra x ticks = {30},
    extra x tick labels = {$a$}
]
\fill[pattern = vertical lines, lightblue] (0,0)-- (0, 100)-- plot[domain=0:30] (\x,{2*atan(5.477/sqrt(\x))*1/\x}) --(30,0) --cycle;
    \draw[ultra thick, samples = 1000] plot[domain=0:100] (\x,{2*atan(5.477/sqrt(\x))*1/\x});
    

\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{tikzfigure}

\vspace{1em}

And it does! $\dfrac{\braket{Kf_a|f_a}}{||f_a||^2} = \dfrac{1}{\ln(a)}\displaystyle\int_{0}^{+\infty} \dfrac{2}{x}\arctan\left(\dfrac{\sqrt{a}}{\sqrt{x}}\right) \mathrm{d}x \geq \dfrac{1}{\ln(a)}\displaystyle\int_{a^{\varepsilon/\pi}}^{a} \dfrac{2}{x}\arctan\left(\dfrac{\sqrt{a}}{\sqrt{a^{\varepsilon/\pi}}}\right) \mathrm{d}x

\medskip

$\hspace{10em} = 2\dfrac{\ln(a^{1 - \varepsilon/\pi})}{\ln(a)}\arctan\left(\dfrac{\sqrt{a}}{\sqrt{a^{\varepsilon/\pi}}}\right) \longrightarrow \pi (1 - \dfrac{\varepsilon}{\pi}) = \pi - \varepsilon$, as $a \longrightarrow +\infty$

\bigskip

This holds for any fixed $\varepsilon \in (0, \pi)$, and \textit{a fortiori} for all $\varepsilon > 0$.
\bigskip

$\therefore \forall \varepsilon > 0\, \, \exists a > 1, \, \dfrac{\braket{Kf_a|f_a}}{||f_a||^2} \geq \pi - \varepsilon \implies \text{\boxed{\pi = \sup\limits_{f \ne 0} \dfrac{\braket{Kf|f}}{||f||^2} = ||K||_2}}$ \qed

}

    \column{0.32}
    \block{Hamiltonian in Quantum Mechanics}{
       \hspace*{10mm} The study of $L^2$ operators turns out to be important in quantum mechanics, as many problems consist in solving the eigenvalue equation of the Hamiltonian operator $\hat{H} := -\dfrac{\hbar}{2m}\nabla^2 + \hat{V}$ (where $\hbar = \frac{h}{2\pi}$ is the reduced Planck constant, and $\hat{V}$ is the potential operator)\footnote{3}.
        
        \bigskip
        \bigskip


    \begin{minipage}{0.62\linewidth}
        For example, consider the one-dimensional \textit{infinite} potential well problem presented in $[\cite{2}]$. Assume a particle of mass $m$ is confined to an infinite tube of diameter $L$. By convention say the potential within is $0$. Let the potential outside be $+\infty$, so that the particle can never escape no matter its kinetic energy.
    \end{minipage}    
    \hfill
                    \begin{minipage}{0.3\linewidth}
                    \vspace{-1em}
        \begin{tikzfigure}[1-D potential well]
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale = 3]
        
    \fill[lightblue, horizontal lines]
        (0, 0) rectangle (0.5, 2)
        (2, 0) rectangle (2.5, 2);

    \vandbarrier{0.5}
    \vandbarrier{2.5}
    \vabove{1}
    \vabove{2}
    \node[anchor = north] at (0.5, 0)   {\scriptsize 0};
    \node[anchor = north] at (2, 0)   {\scriptsize $L$};
    \node[anchor = south] at (1.2, 0.8) {\small $V = 0$};
    \node[anchor = north] at (0.25, 2.3) {\small $V=\infty$};
    \node[anchor = north] at (2.2, 2.3) {\small $V=\infty$};

    \draw[<->, ultra thick] (0, 0) to (2.5, 0);
    \draw[->, ultra thick]  (0.5, 0) to (0.5, 2);
    \draw[->, ultra thick]  (2, 0) to (2, 2);

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{tikzfigure}
\end{minipage}


\bigskip


    \medskip
    
    Let $\ket{\psi}$ be the quantum state of the system, and $\psi$ its associated wave function, \textit{ie} it defines a probability amplitude. Hence, $\psi(x) = 0 \,\, \forall x \notin (0,L)$ (value at the barriers is enforced by the continuity of $\psi$). We can now solve:
    
    \bigskip
    \bigskip

    \begin{thmbox}[L]{Time-independent Schrödinger's equation}
$\hat{H}\ket{\psi} = E\ket{\psi}$, with $E$ the energy of the system.
\end{thmbox}

in one-dimension. Since $\hat{V} = 0\,$  within the tube, we get: $-\dfrac{\hbar}{2m}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}^2\psi(x)}{\mathrm{d}x^2} = E\psi(x)$, 

\smallskip

which yields $\psi(x) = A\sin(kx)$ by using the boundary conditions above. And 

\smallskip

$\psi(L) = 0$ enforces that $k$ depends on $n \in \mathbb{N}$: $k_n = \pi n/L$.

\bigskip

\begin{minipage}{0.65\linewidth}

Now, the particle has to be \textbf{somewhere} between $0$ and $L$, and since $\psi$ is a probability amplitude, this implies we need to normalize $\displaystyle\int_{0}^{L} \psi(x)^2 \mathrm{d}x$ for it to equal $1$. This condition enforces $A = \sqrt{2/L}$.

\bigskip

Now, the original ODE tells us that $k = \dfrac{\sqrt{2mE}}{\hbar}$

$\implies E = \dfrac{\hbar^2k_n^2}{2m}$. Energy \textbf{is} quantified! 
\end{minipage}
\hfill
\begin{minipage}{0.3\linewidth}
\begin{tikzfigure}[Max Planck]
\includegraphics[scale = 0.75]{grosbg.jpg}
\end{tikzfigure}
\end{minipage}

\medskip



    }

    \block{Remarks}{
        \vspace{-1em}
    \begin{enumerate}
    \normalsize 
        \item To use the quantum mechanics notation, often used with infinite-dimensional Hilbert spaces, denote by $\ket{.}$ vectors, and by $\braket{.|.}$ the inner product on the space.
        
        \item This choice of function was inspired by that of the user robjohn in a post on the 14th of May 2013 on \textit{Math StackExchange} [\cite{5}]. I, however, tried to simplify the calculations as much as I could to make them easier, and aimed to add a geometrical meaning to that « trick ».
        
        \item Note that $\hat{H}$ is an example of unbounded operator (as it is frequent in quantum physics). One can indeed easily find a bounded function whose laplacian is unbounded.
    \end{enumerate}
    }
